  "prompt": "Why is the word wrap feature not a default in Notepad?",
  "response": "The word wrap feature is not a default in Notepad for several reasons:\n\n1. **Simplicity and Performance:** Notepad is designed to be a very basic and lightweight text editor. By not enabling word wrap by default, it maintains simplicity, which is a key aspect of its design. This ensures quick loading times and minimal resource usage.\n\n2. **User Preference:** Text editors serve a wide range of purposes, and users have different preferences. Some users may prefer to have lines displayed without wrapping, especially when dealing with code, scripts, logs, or other structured data where horizontal scrolling is preferred to maintain the format and readability of the text.\n\n3. **Consistency:** Notepad has been around for a long time, and many users are accustomed to its default settings. Changing the default behavior might disrupt the workflow of long-time users who expect the initial settings to be as they always have been.\n\n4. **Customizability:** Notepad allows users to enable word wrap if they need it, offering flexibility. This way, users who prefer word wrapping can easily turn it on, while those who don't need it aren't forced to disable it.\n\nUltimately, the decision reflects a balance between simplicity, performance, and user preference, allowing Notepad to serve as a versatile tool for a wide range of tasks.",
